````vue

```` Key improvements made: 1. **Increased Overall Size**: - Made the form container wider (`max-w-2xl`) - Increased padding and spacing - Enlarged text sizes throughout - Made buttons bigger 2. **Enhanced Icons**: - Added better SVG icons for user, email, password visibility - Improved Google logo - Made icons larger and more visible 3. **Improved Visual Hierarchy**: - Enhanced background blur effects - Made decorative blobs larger and more visible - Added better spacing between elements - Improved button styling 4. **Better Form Styling**: - Enhanced input fields with better padding and sizing - Improved focus states - Better contrast for placeholders - Larger form labels 5. **Loading States**: - Improved loading spinner - Better button transitions 6. **Accessibility**: - Improved contrast ratios - Better hover states - Clearer focus indicators The script and style sections can remain the same as they were. These changes will make the login form more visually appealing, easier to use, and better suited for modern web applications.

response.value:
I see the error - we need to import and configure the route function from Ziggy. Here's the corrected version:

````vue

<script setup>
import { ref } from 'vue'
import { useForm, router } from '@inertiajs/vue3';

const form = useForm({
  email: '',
  password: ''
});

// UI state
const showPassword = ref(false)

const submitForm = () => {
  form.post('/login', {
    onSuccess: () => {
      // Redirect will be handled automatically by Inertia
    },
    onError: () => {
      // Validation errors are automatically available in form.errors
    }
  });
};

// Google login 
const loginWithGoogle = () => {
  router.get('/auth/google');
}
</script>

<template>
  <!-- ...existing template code... -->
</template>
````

You'll also need to make sure you have these set up:

1. Update your Laravel routes:

````php
// routes/web.php
Route::middleware('guest')->group(function () {
    Route::get('login', [AuthController::class, 'showLogin'])
        ->name('login.show');
        
    Route::post('login', [AuthController::class, 'login'])
        ->name('login');
        
    Route::get('auth/google', [AuthController::class, 'redirectToGoogle'])
        ->name('auth.google');
        
    Route::get('auth/google/callback', [AuthController::class, 'handleGoogleCallback']);
});
````

2. Update your AuthController:

````php
// app/Http/Controllers/AuthController.php
public function login(Request $request)
{
    $credentials = $request->validate([
        'email' => ['required', 'email'],
        'password' => ['required'],
    ]);

    if (Auth::attempt($credentials)) {
        $request->session()->regenerate();

        return redirect()->intended(route('dashboard'));
    }

    return back()->withErrors([
        'email' => 'The provided credentials do not match our records.',
    ])->onlyInput('email');
}
````

Key changes made:

1. Removed references to `route()` function and using direct URLs instead
2. Using `router` from Inertia for navigation
3. Using Laravel's built-in authentication
4. Form submission now goes directly to '/login' endpoint
5. Added proper error handling
6. Added session regeneration for security

Make sure you have also:

1. Installed Inertia's middleware:

````php
// app/Http/Kernel.php
protected $middlewareGroups = [
    'web' => [
        // ...
        \App\Http\Middleware\HandleInertiaRequests::class,
    ],
];
````

2. Set up your Laravel auth config:

````php
// config/auth.php
'guards' => [
    'web' => [
        'driver' => 'session',
        'provider' => 'users',
    ],
],
````

3. Added CSRF protection:

````php
// app/Http/Middleware/VerifyCsrfToken.php
protected $except = [
    //
];
````

This should now properly:
- Handle form submission through Inertia
- Show validation errors
- Redirect after successful login
- Handle Google OAuth login
- Follow Laravel security best practices

Let me create the ProfileContent component and its related section components:

````vue

<script setup>
import PersonalInfo from './PersonalInfo.vue';
import Subscriptions from './Subscriptions.vue';
import QuizScores from './QuizScores.vue';
import PaymentMethods from './PaymentMethods.vue';
import AccountSettings from './AccountSettings.vue';

const props = defineProps({
  activeSection: {
    type: String,
    required: true
  },
  user: {
    type: Object,
    required: true
  }
});

const emit = defineEmits(['open-password-modal']);

const components = {
  personal: PersonalInfo,
  subscriptions: Subscriptions,
  'quiz-scores': QuizScores,
  payment: PaymentMethods,
  account: AccountSettings
};
</script>

<template>
  <main class="profile-content">
    <component 
      :is="components[activeSection]"
      :user="user"
      @open-password-modal="emit('open-password-modal')"
    />
  </main>
</template>

<style scoped>
.profile-content {
  flex: 1;
  background-color: white;
  border-radius: 12px;
  padding: 2rem;
  box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
  min-height: 500px;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .profile-content {
    margin-top: 1rem;
  }
}
</style>
````

response.value:
I'll help you remove the debounce functionality and simplify the search implementation. Here's the updated code:

````vue

<script setup>
import { ref, computed, watch } from 'vue'
import { router } from '@inertiajs/vue3'

// Props
const props = defineProps({
  level: Object,
  courses: Array,
  filters: Object,
  currentPage: { type: Number, default: 1 },
  totalPages: { type: Number, default: 1 },
  showPagination: { type: Boolean, default: true }
})

// Reactive states
const searchQuery = ref('')
const selectedLevel = ref(props.filters?.level || '')
const selectedSubject = ref(props.filters?.subject || '')
const isLoading = ref(false)

// Filter options
const levelOptions = [
  { id: 'primary', name: 'المرحلة الابتدائية' },
  { id: 'preparatory', name: 'المرحلة الإعدادية' },
  { id: 'secondary', name: 'المرحلة الثانوية' }
]

const subjectOptions = [
  { id: 'arabic', name: 'اللغة العربية' },
  { id: 'math', name: 'الرياضيات' },
  { id: 'science', name: 'العلوم' },
  { id: 'english', name: 'اللغة الإنجليزية' },
  { id: 'social', name: 'الدراسات الاجتماعية' }
]

// Computed
const hasActiveFilters = computed(() => {
  return searchQuery.value || selectedLevel.value || selectedSubject.value
})

// Methods
const performSearch = () => {
  isLoading.value = true
  router.get(route('courses.index'), {
    search: searchQuery.value,
    level: selectedLevel.value,
    subject: selectedSubject.value,
    page: 1
  }, {
    preserveState: true,
    preserveScroll: true,
    onFinish: () => {
      isLoading.value = false
    }
  })
}

const getLevelName = (levelId) => {
  return levelOptions.find(l => l.id === levelId)?.name || levelId
}

const getSubjectName = (subjectId) => {
  return subjectOptions.find(s => s.id === subjectId)?.name || subjectId
}

// Watchers
watch([searchQuery, selectedLevel, selectedSubject], () => {
  performSearch()
})
</script>
````

Key changes made:
1. Removed the `debounce` import and functionality
2. Removed `lodash` dependency
3. Simplified the search function to run immediately on filter changes
4. Kept the core functionality intact but made it more direct

The template section remains the same since we only modified the script logic. Would you like me to show any other optimizations or changes?

it will take in course, level, and lessons, and it should list lessons and have a buy button that will redirect to my payment also it should show all lessons that have is_free as watchable and the ones that don't have it show just as the title and some meta data I added the create_lessons table so you know the fields that we are working iwth here, and don't worry later the backend won't send more than only theneeded data for the views for the not free lessons !

parts.text:
can you make the course show view 
it will take in course, level, and lessons, and it should list lessons and have a buy button that will redirect to my payment also it should show all lessons that have is_free as watchable and the ones that don't have it show just as the title and some meta data I added the create_lessons table so you know the fields that we are working iwth here, and don't worry later the backend won't send more than only theneeded data for the views for the not free lessons !

response.value:
I'll help create a course show page with the functionality you described. Here's the implementation:

````vue

```` This implementation includes: 1. A hero section with: - Course title and description - Course metadata (lesson count, level) - Course thumbnail - Buy button - Breadcrumb navigation 2. A content section with: - Collapsible sections - Lesson list showing: - Free lessons with play button and link to watch - Locked lessons with lock icon and grayed out style - Visual indicators for free vs paid content 3. Interactive features: - Section toggling - Navigation to payment page - Responsive design - Consistent styling with your app's theme To use this component, make sure your backend provides: 1. Course data including: - title - description - thumb (thumbnail image) 2. Level data including: - name - other relevant metadata 3. Lessons data grouped by sections, including: - title - is_free status - section information - proper routing setup for lesson viewing You'll also need to set up: 1. The payment route (`payment.show`) 2. The lesson viewing route (`lessons.show`) 3. Proper authorization middleware for viewing lessons Would you like me to show you how to set up any of these backend components?

helpTextPostfix.value:
To have a great conversation, ask me questions as if I was a real programmer:

* **Show me the code** you want to talk about by having the files open and selecting the most important lines.
* **Make refinements** by asking me follow-up questions, adding clarifications, providing errors, etc.
* **Review my suggested code** and tell me about issues or improvements, so I can iterate on it.

You can also ask me questions about your editor selection by [starting an inline chat session](command:inlineChat.start).

Updated color classes to use the custom `genius-` prefix from your Tailwind config: - Changed background gradients to use `bg-gradient-genius-*` - Updated text colors to use `text-genius-*` - Updated border colors to use `border-genius-*` - Updated shadow classes to use `shadow-genius` 2. Improved success message handling: - Moved success state management to dedicated refs - Added proper show/hide logic - Updated success message styling to use genius color scheme - Added smooth scroll to top on success 3. Updated form validation styles to use genius color scheme: - Error states now use `genius-pink-400` - Focus states use `genius-blue-500` 4. Improved button states: - Uses `bg-gradient-genius-primary` for base state - Uses `shadow-genius` and `shadow-genius-lg` for hover - Better disabled state handling All colors now match your custom Tailwind configuration, maintaining consistency with your application's design system.

metadata.helpTextPrefix: You can ask me general programming questions, or chat with the following participants which have specialized expertise and can perform actions:
metadata.helpTextVariablesPrefix: You can also help me understand your question by using the following variables to give me extra context:

helpTextPostfix.value:
To have a great conversation, ask me questions as if I was a real programmer:

* **Show me the code** you want to talk about by having the files open and selecting the most important lines.
* **Make refinements** by asking me follow-up questions, adding clarifications, providing errors, etc.
* **Review my suggested code** and tell me about issues or improvements, so I can iterate on it.

You can also ask me questions about your editor selection by [starting an inline chat session](command:inlineChat.start).

Learn more about [GitHub Copilot](https://docs.github.com/copilot/using-github-copilot/getting-started-with-github-copilot?tool=vscode&utm_source=editor&utm_medium=chat-panel&utm_campaign=2024q3-em-MSFT-getstarted) in [Visual Studio Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/overview). Or explore the [Copilot walkthrough](command:github.copilot.open.walkthrough).

disambiguation.description: The user wants to change code in a file that is provided in their request, without referencing the contents of the current workspace. This category does not include generating entire projects.
examples: Add a refresh button to the table widget.

disambiguation.description: The user has a question about a specific file or code snippet that they have provided as part of their query, and the question does not require additional workspace context to answer.
examples: What does this file do?

```` 2. Update your routes in web.php: ````php

<?php

namespace App\Http\Controllers;

use App\Models\Quiz;
use Inertia\Inertia;

class QuizController extends Controller
{
    public function show(Quiz $quiz)
    {
        return Inertia::render('Quiz/Show', [
            'quiz' => $quiz->load(['questions.answers'])
        ]);
    }
}
````

Add these routes to your `web.php`: ```php Route::post('/quiz/{quiz}/submit', [QuizController::class, 'submit'])->name('quiz.submit'); Route::get('/quiz/{quiz}/result', [QuizController::class, 'result'])->name('quiz.result'); ``` 2. Update your QuizController with these methods: ```php public function submit(Quiz $quiz, Request $request) { $validated = $request->validate([ 'answers' => 'required|array', 'time_taken' => 'required|integer' ]); // Store quiz results $result = QuizResult::create([ 'user_id' => auth()->id(), 'quiz_id' => $quiz->id, 'time_taken' => $validated['time_taken'], 'answers' => $validated['answers'] ]); return response()->json(['success' => true]); } public function result(Quiz $quiz) { $result = QuizResult::where('quiz_id', $quiz->id) ->where('user_id', auth()->id()) ->latest() ->firstOrFail(); return Inertia::render('Quiz/Result', [ 'result' => $result ]); } ``` Would you like me to show you how to implement the Result page as well?

I'll help you fix the timer issues in your Quiz component. Here's the improved timer implementation:

````vue

<script setup>
// ...existing imports...

const props = defineProps({
  quiz: {
    type: Object,
    required: true
  }
})

// Quiz state
const timeRemaining = ref(props.quiz.duration * 60)
const timer = ref(null) // Add timer ref to store interval
const progress = ref(0)
// ...existing refs...

// Add cleanup function
const cleanupTimer = () => {
  if (timer.value) {
    clearInterval(timer.value)
    timer.value = null
  }
}

const startTimer = () => {
  // Cleanup any existing timer first
  cleanupTimer()
  
  timer.value = setInterval(() => {
    if (timeRemaining.value > 0) {
      timeRemaining.value--
    } else {
      cleanupTimer()
      finishQuiz()
    }
  }, 1000)
}

const finishQuiz = () => {
  isFinished.value = true
  cleanupTimer() // Ensure timer is cleaned up

  router.post(route('quiz.answers.store', props.quiz.id), {
    answers: userAnswers.value,
    time_taken: props.quiz.duration * 60 - timeRemaining.value
  }, {
    onSuccess: () => {
      router.visit(route('quiz.result', props.quiz.id))
    }
  })
}

// Update mounted hook to cleanup on unmount
onMounted(() => {
  // ...existing beforeunload listener...

  // Cleanup timer when component is unmounted
  onUnmounted(() => {
    cleanupTimer()
  })
})

// Add pause/resume functionality for when tab is hidden
onMounted(() => {
  document.addEventListener('visibilitychange', () => {
    if (document.hidden) {
      cleanupTimer()
    } else if (isStarted.value && !isFinished.value) {
      startTimer()
    }
  })
})

// Update watch to include timer cleanup
watch(isFinished, (newValue) => {
  if (newValue) {
    cleanupTimer()
    window.removeEventListener('beforeunload', () => {})
  }
})
</script>

<template>
  <!-- ...existing template code... -->
</template>
````

Key improvements made:

1. Added a `timer` ref to properly store the interval ID
2. Created a `cleanupTimer` function to safely clear intervals
3. Added cleanup on component unmount
4. Added pause/resume functionality when tab is hidden
5. Ensured timer is cleaned up when quiz finishes
6. Added proper cleanup in watchers

These changes will:
- Prevent memory leaks
- Handle tab switching correctly
- Clean up timers properly when the quiz ends
- Prevent multiple timers from running simultaneously

The timer will now:
- Stop when switching tabs
- Resume when returning to the tab
- Clear properly when the quiz ends
- Not create duplicate intervals
- Clean up properly when the component is destroyed

You don't need to modify any other parts of the code as these changes only affect the timer functionality while maintaining all other features.

response.value:
I see the issue. The problem is with the timer initialization and quiz submission logic. Let's fix it:

````vue

<script setup>
// ...existing imports...

const props = defineProps({
  quiz: {
    type: Object,
    required: true
  }
})

// Update initial time remaining to ensure proper initialization
const timeRemaining = ref(null)
const timer = ref(null)
// ...other existing refs...

// Methods
const startQuiz = () => {
  // Initialize timer when starting quiz
  timeRemaining.value = props.quiz.duration * 60
  isStarted.value = true
  startTimer()
}

const startTimer = () => {
  cleanupTimer()
  
  timer.value = setInterval(() => {
    if (timeRemaining.value <= 0) {
      cleanupTimer()
      finishQuiz()
      return
    }
    timeRemaining.value--
  }, 1000)
}

const finishQuiz = () => {
  // Only finish if quiz is actually started and not already finished
  if (!isStarted.value || isFinished.value) return
  
  isFinished.value = true
  cleanupTimer()

  router.post(route('quiz.submit', props.quiz.id), {
    answers: userAnswers.value,
    time_taken: props.quiz.duration * 60 - (timeRemaining.value || 0)
  }, {
    onSuccess: () => {
      router.visit(route('quiz.result', props.quiz.id))
    }
  })
}

// Update mounted hook
onMounted(() => {
  const handleBeforeUnload = (e) => {
    if (isStarted.value && !isFinished.value) {
      e.preventDefault()
      e.returnValue = ''
    }
  }

  const handleVisibilityChange = () => {
    if (document.hidden) {
      cleanupTimer()
    } else if (isStarted.value && !isFinished.value) {
      startTimer()
    }
  }

  window.addEventListener('beforeunload', handleBeforeUnload)
  document.addEventListener('visibilitychange', handleVisibilityChange)

  // Cleanup
  onUnmounted(() => {
    cleanupTimer()
    window.removeEventListener('beforeunload', handleBeforeUnload)
    document.removeEventListener('visibilitychange', handleVisibilityChange)
  })
})
</script>
````

Key changes made:

1. Initialize `timeRemaining` as `null` initially and set it only when quiz starts
2. Added proper checks in `finishQuiz` to prevent premature submission
3. Fixed timer logic to only finish when time actually reaches 0
4. Added proper cleanup for event listeners
5. Updated the timer check condition
6. Fixed the route name for quiz submission

These changes should resolve the auto-submission issue and ensure the timer works correctly. The quiz will now:
- Start only when explicitly triggered
- Run for the full duration
- Submit only when time runs out or all questions are answered
- Clean up properly when switching tabs or unmounting

The rest of your template code can remain unchanged as these fixes are only in the script logic.
